EU Commission proposes new court in dispute over TTIP
To defuse the dispute over the planned transatlantic free trade agreement TTIP, the EU Commission has proposed a comprehensive reform of the current arbitration system.
The controversial private arbitration mechanisms for disputes between corporations and states are to be replaced by a more transparent system, which corresponds to much more traditional courts in its functioning.
"We want to put in place a system that people trust," said Commissioner Cecilia Malmström at the presentation.
The Swede intends to introduce the proposal as a European negotiating position in the free trade talks with the USA.
The German government announced support.
TTIP is to create the largest free trade area in the world with 800 million people.
Specifically, the plans to reform current arbitration procedures foresee that EU countries and the US will jointly select independent judges for a new Investment Court.
They are expected to come in equal parts from the EU, the USA and third countries.
A second instance is also envisaged for the first time.
It would make it possible to appeal against judgments.
Up to now, the parties to the proceedings have agreed among themselves on arbitrators, and there has been no possibility of appealing against their judgments.
In the discussion of the past few months, it became clear that citizens did not trust the old ISDS system in terms of fairness and justice, Malmström commented.
In the long term, it says it wants to work towards an International Investment Court.
There, for example, disputes between Chinese companies and EU states could also be resolved.
Investor-state arbitration (ISDS), which is mainly demanded by large corporations, is considered one of the main reasons for the great resistance in Europe to TTIP.
Traditional arbitration courts are criticized by opponents as a kind of parallel justice that allows companies to seek damages at the expense of taxpayers, overturn national laws, or enforce lowering consumer and environmental standards.
In initial statements, anti-TTIP organisations such as Campact described the proposals of the EU Commission as insufficient.
The main criticism was that they should not apply to the already negotiated free trade agreement with Canada (Ceta).
The German State Secretary for Economic Affairs Matthias Machnig (SPD), on the other hand, described the plans as a major step forward.
The Commission took into account key points that Federal Minister for Economic Affairs Sigmar Gabriel and other EU Trade Ministers had worked out in the spring in the reform.
The old system of private arbitration was off the table.
The French Government also welcomed Malmström's plans.
The European business association BusinessEurope warned that too many new rules restrict the business community's ability to take legal action.
Small and medium-sized enterprises in particular could be put at a disadvantage, it said.
It remained unclear on Wednesday when the talks on the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) could be concluded.
Negotiations have been ongoing since mid-2013.
However, the issue of investor protection has not yet been discussed with the USA.
Originally, a framework for the agreement was supposed to be in place by the end of this year.
This date is no longer valid.
