Pound rises as UK wage growth accelerates
The pound jumped after data showed a rise in UK wage growth, while the FTSE 100 was boosted by bidding target SABMiller.
Earnings excluding bonuses in the UK grew by 2.9% between May and July compared with the same period last year.
That percentage was the fastest since 2009 and provided an estimate of when interest rates would rise.
The pound rose more than 1% against the dollar to $1.5505 and was up 0.84% against the euro to €1.3730.
The FTSE 100 index closed up 1.49% at 6,229.21.
SABMiller was the standout stock in the market, jumping 20 per cent after rival AB InBev's takeover bid was accepted.
A transaction would combine the world's two largest breweries and bring together brands such as Budweiser, Stella Artois, Peroni and Grolsch.
Burberry shares were 0.9% higher after encouraging news from luxury goods group Richemont.
Richemont's latest sales figures beat expectations and also showed that sales in China - a key market for Burberry - are growing again.
Shares in Glencore rose 5% after the mining giant said it had raised $2.5bn through a share sale as part of its debt reduction strategy.
Shares in packaging and paper group Mondi were the biggest losers on the index, down 4.3% after Goldman Sachs cut its rating on the company to "sell."
JD Sports rose 3.1% after the sportswear company reported a pre-tax profit of £46.6m for the half-year.
The boss of JD Sports says higher wages are jeopardising expansion.
JD Sports chief executive Peter Cowgill says a higher minimum wage for UK workers could mean "more spending power in the pockets of potential customers."
But that spending power is unlikely to offset the higher labor costs at his company, he says.
The cost could hit JD Sports' expansion plans, he added, and that could mean fewer additional jobs.
