Pegida poster brings Lebanese to potato donor idea
Potatoes or kebabs?
It works both ways - in the potato döner developed by Hani Alhay, the Oldenburg snack bar owner.
Inspired by the slogan "potato instead of kebab" on a poster of the Pegida movement, Alhay put potato and meat together on a skewer.
The idea came to him from a poster at a Pegida demonstration with the inscription "Potatoes instead of kebabs," which he had accidentally seen on television.
Since then, a barbecue skewer stocked with meat and potatoes has been turning in his shop.
"This is multiculturalism for the stomach," Alhay says.
The Lebanese has since registered the idea with the Patent Office in Munich.
According to the authority, it has recently been protected there as a utility model.
Alhay therefore does not want to reveal how much meat and potatoes the skewer contains.
Just so much: "It tastes even better together," he says.
Culinary international understanding is also well received by its customers.
Metcash launches grounding campaign to combat Aldi incursion
Metcash is trying to protect IGA stores from an Aldi surge in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a ground-breaking campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia ahead of a $700 million Aldi invasion.
As Aldi prepares to open two distribution centres and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and marketing via social media, as well as events such as the Adelaide show.
IGA retailers and suppliers are jumping on board, with brands such as Dunsborough-based ice cream maker Simmo distributing samples in IGA stores and shopkeepers selling discounted tickets for the South Australian Football League to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to release more details of its defence strategy on September 29, when the food, alcohol and appliance wholesaler holds its annual investor strategy day.
The stakes are high as South Australia and Western Australia account for almost 30 per cent of Metcash's IGA stores and generate higher profit margins than Metcash's IGA network in the eastern states.
Shoppers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland - more than 30 per cent in South Australia and 24 per cent in Western Australia compared to around 14 per cent in the eastern states.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe Aldi will snatch away around 5 per cent of the grocery market in those two states 12 months after opening its first stores, taking sales away from all existing players but mainly independent retailers.
According to a report released this week, analyst Tom Kierath of Morgan Stanley estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in revenue a year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in SA and 30 in WA next year, generating sales of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in food and grocery and volumes on Metcash's high fixed cost basis could cost Metcash about $13 million in earnings before interest and tax, Mr Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA shoppers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley expects Metcash's food and grocery sales to fall 3.8 percent in 2016, 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, and to reduce its market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, leading fund manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of Magellan Financial Group, told a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash was likely to disappear within a decade.
Metcash declined to respond publicly to Mr. Douglass's comments.
But it is understood a Metcash board member made contact with Mr Douglass last week.
IGA's market share has fallen from 18% to 14% since 2010, and revenue from Metcash's food and grocery business, which supplies about 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen 43% since 2012, reflecting operational deleveraging while putting pressure on sales and margins.
However, the wholesaler is fighting back, investing more than $150 million to align sales prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products every week and to help IGA retailers improve their stores by growing fresh food faster and providing a better choice of private label food.
Metcash chief executive Ian Morrice says price adjustments and store refurbishment programs will pick up steam and hopes the wholesaler will return to profit growth in 2017 for the first time in four years.
Thanasi Kokkinakis backed by Australian Tennis Federation president Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves more praise than criticism for his behaviour.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral damage" in the recent storm surrounding his friend Nick Kyrgios and deserves praise rather than criticism for his own behaviour, according to Australian Tennis Association president Steve Healy.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo often referred to as' Special Ks', came under the spotlight following Kyrgios' infamous altercation with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifying match in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the umpire, with Harrison exclaiming: 'Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios and I should have beaten him.'
While he was last seen smashing a tennis racket after cramp thwarted a potential US Open win by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was steadfastly defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, competing with Sam Groth for second place in the singles behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against Great Britain.
"One thing I'm pretty angry about is the fact that I think Thanasi got dragged into the argument a little bit," Healy said.
He broke a racquet when he lost to cramp in the US Open, but he is not the first player to break a racquet out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know that he is not proud of it.
But, really, he did extremely well in the US Open, even in the pretty provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of credit.
He has a great team around him, he has a great family around him and I think he was treated a little too harshly.
He's a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard and he fits into the team and so on, he's never had a problem with the other players, he's respected in the locker room, he trains hard, he's in good shape, he's a very stable and mature young guy and I think he deserves to be judged on his own merits.
Healy also backed the decision not to include Kyrgios in the crucial preliminary decider, which begins on Friday, describing the "joint decision" as the right one for everyone, but he assured the Canberra man he would return to the team as a long-term fixture. "
"First of all, we want the team to be fully focused on the competition and not on all the controversies around [Kyrgios]," Healy said.
And I think Nick has risen very quickly, as people like Federer and Murray have pointed out. He is rising in the public eye, and he has made some terrible mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we are trying to support him, we are trying to make him understand the consequences of his actions. I think some time out of the spotlight, when he can only think about it, is appropriate, and it is best for the team and it is best for him.
Europe's refugee crisis: Hungary declares state of emergency, closes border, holds back refugees
Hungary declared a state of emergency and sealed its southern border with Serbia on Tuesday, detaining anyone who tried to enter the country illegally, all with the aim of halting the flow of migrants.
Chaos ensued at the border as hundreds of migrants massed in a no-man's-land and Serbian officials reacted with outrage.
The people who had fled the violence were stuck for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two checkpoints of the countries, erecting tents and settling there.
But frustrations mounted.
As a police helicopter hovered overhead, migrants chanted "Open the border!" and shouted insults at Hungarian riot police.
Some refused food and water in protest.
Serbia's foreign minister said it was "unacceptable" that migrants were being sent back from Hungary, while more and more were arriving from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution, not collateral damage.
Talks with Brussels and other countries must take place in the coming days, said Ivica Dacic in Prague.
The turmoil on the Hungarian-Serbian border came a day after the 28-nation bloc failed to agree on a common immigration policy at a contentious meeting in Brussels.
However, ministers agreed to share responsibility for 40,000 people seeking refuge in caught-off-guard Italy and Greece, expressing hope that an agreement would eventually be reached - next month or by the end of the year - that EU states would take in a further 120,000 refugees, including some from Hungary.
Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria on Tuesday called for a special European Union summit to discuss the continent's immigration crisis.
Hungary, however, did not pin its hopes on early action from Brussels or its neighbours.
A state of emergency declared on Tuesday in two southern regions gave authorities more powers to deal with the crisis, allowing them to close roads and speed up asylum procedures.
Meanwhile, Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto said that his country is also planning to build a barbed-wire fence along its border with Romania to stop the flow of migrants through the country - after completing a fence on the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reported that even prison inmates were used in the race to build the barbed-wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, Hungary has become a major bottleneck and entry point into the European Union for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East.
However, Prime Minister Viktor Orban has insisted that most arrivals are economic migrants seeking a better life, not war refugees entitled to protection - a view strongly at odds with other EU states, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, make it a crime to cross the border or damage the 4-meter (13-foot) high fence that the government has built along the southern border with Serbia. These laws also stipulate higher prison sentences for convicted traffickers.
"Due to the situation created by the mass migration, the Hungarian government declares a state of emergency," government spokesman Zoltan Kovacs told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
Let us be very clear: illegal border crossing is a crime.
Parliament has yet to approve the military's deployment, which is expected next week, but Associated Press reporters have seen heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and dogs at the border for days.
Gyorgy Bakondi, a national security adviser to Orban, said authorities caught 45 people trying to cross the border and 15 others had already penetrated deeper into the country.
They come over by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
Authorities are quickly repairing the fence.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a train carrying barbed wire arrived to close the borders.
Chaos surrounded the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, as Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process people's data and pushed a crowd to get inside.
About 20 managed to get in, but thousands remained outside.
Another group of migrants blocked the main highway linking Serbia and Hungary, saying they would refuse food and water until they were allowed into Hungary.
Election 2016: Hillary Clinton's lead over Bernie Sanders halved in national poll
Former Secretary of State Hillary Clinton still holds a double-digit lead in the Democratic race for the national nomination, but Sen. Bernie Sanders is gaining ground against her.
Clinton now has the support of 47 percent of Democratic voters in the primaries (up from 58 percent previously), while Sanders is in second place with 27 percent (up from 17 percent).
Vice President Joe Biden, who has not yet announced whether he will run for president, has the support of 15 percent of Democratic primary voters.
With more than five months to go before the primaries begin, most Democratic voters say it's too early to tell which candidate they'll support.
But Clinton's supporters are more consistent in their choice than the other candidates.
Since the CBS News poll, Clinton has lost among a number of demographics, while Sanders has made some gains.
Clinton holds a large lead among women and moderates, but those leads have narrowed.
Her support among men has dropped significantly, and Sanders is only 5 points behind.
Clinton's advantage among Democratic voters under 50 has evaporated, and she and Sanders are now level.
Clinton still has a big lead among older voters, however.
Last month, Clinton was ahead of Sanders by double digits among liberals, but Sanders now has a 5-point lead among that group.
About half of Democratic primary voters nationwide say they would enthusiastically support Clinton if she were nominated by the party.
A quarter would support her with some reservations, and another 15 percent would support her only because she is the nominee.
Six per cent would not support it.
Perhaps not surprisingly, Clinton's current supporters are particularly enthusiastic about her.
Views are more mixed among those who do not currently support Clinton - only about a quarter would enthusiastically support her.
While 48 percent of Democratic primary voters say they enthusiastically support Clinton, fewer Republican voters say so about their front-runner, Donald Trump (35 percent).
When Clinton's supporters are asked in an open question why they want her to be the nominee, the most common answer is that she has the right experience (16 percent), followed by the view that it is time for a woman to become president (13 percent) and that she is the best candidate for the job (10 percent).
Clinton's supporters also cite her connection to Bill Clinton (9 percent).
Agreement to deal with the problems and eligibility are also cited.
With the vice president weighing potential for the presidency, 57 percent of Democratic primary voters want him in the race - though a third believe he shouldn't.
When Democratic primary voters are asked who would be their second choice for the party, Biden leads.
Of Clinton's supporters, more than half say Biden would be their second choice far ahead of Sanders.
If Biden decides not to run for the Democratic nomination, Hillary Clinton's lead over Sanders increases from 20 points with Biden in the race to 30 points without him in the race.
Fifty-five percent of Democratic voters see Clinton as the candidate with the best chance of winning the election, but that number has dropped from 78 percent last month.
Biden is second by far in that measure, but the percentage who see him as the "most electable" has risen.
Still, when asked what is more important to a candidate, Democratic voters cite questions about eligibility.
Much like last month, not a single Democratic candidate or potential candidate stands out as unacceptable to these primary voters.
The Democratic candidates, or potential candidates, perform well on some key traits among voters in their party's primaries.
Majorities view Clinton, Sanders, and Biden as honest and trustworthy, with strong leadership qualities.
Biden performs best among the three candidates on honesty, while Clinton's strength is leadership.
Thirty percent of Democratic voters don't believe Clinton is honest and trustworthy, twice as many say the same about Sanders (15 percent), but 27 percent don't have an opinion of him.
Democratic primary voters also generally view Clinton, Sanders and Biden ideologically in line with their views.
By all those measures, about a quarter of Democratic voters don't have a view of Sanders.
As questions continue to be asked about Hillary Clinton's use of a personal email address and server during her tenure as secretary of state, most Democratic primary voters are satisfied with her explanation of the matter, saying it has not affected their overall views.
But it's a different story in the American public at large.
Half of Americans are now dissatisfied with their explanation, while only about a third are satisfied.
Public opinion on the issue was split in March, shortly after the issue came to light.
Most Americans said the email controversy had no impact on their overall views of Clinton, though 36 percent said their opinion of her had worsened.
It's mostly Republicans, more than six in 10, who say their views of Clinton have deteriorated.
While Clinton is viewed as honest and trustworthy by her party's voters, it remains a problem for her among registered voters overall: Only 32 percent see her as honest and trustworthy, eight percent less than last month and 15 points lower since May.
Sixty-two percent of eligible voters do not consider her an honest and trustworthy person.
At the same time, 55 percent of registered voters nationwide also view Trump as dishonest and untrustworthy.
Clinton and Trump, however, get high marks for leadership.
Of the six candidates tested, Biden, Carson and Bush do best on honesty.
A majority view Sanders as honest, but as with Carson, many have no opinion of him.
The margin of error for the sample of 351 Democratic voters in the primaries is 6 percentage points.
Ben Carson moves close behind Donald Trump in national poll
Ben Carson is close behind Donald Trump in latest CBS News / New York Times poll
The two candidates now account for half the support of voters in the new poll, and others are losing ground dramatically.
Republican voters nationwide continue to support Trump in large numbers, with support growing from 23% in the last CBS poll conducted before last month's Fox News debate to 27% in Tuesday's poll.
But Carson shot up from 6% to 23% over the same period.
The poll also found Carson doing well among demographic groups, outperforming Trump among Republican voters with higher education.
The rest of the field, with the exception of Carly Fiorina and Ohio Gov. John Kasich, is tied with Wisconsin Gov. Scott Walker, who has fallen the deepest, from 10% support last month to 2% now.
Former Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, former Arkansas Gov. Mike Huckabee and Florida Sen. Marco Rubio are in third place with 6%.
The margin of error for the sample of 376 Republican voters in this latest poll is plus or minus 6% and was conducted in September.
The latest CNN / ORC poll, released last week, shows Carson rising in the polls - landing 19% support among Republicans, behind Trump with 32% support.
The latest ABC News / Washington Post poll also showed Trump well ahead of Carson.
Facing a rising Carson last week, Trump took some swipes at the former neurosurgeon even after Carson apologized for questioning Trump's faith.
"We need energy," Trump said Saturday during a campaign appearance in Iowa.
Pleasant bathing temperatures: The eastern Mediterranean is currently up to 29 degrees.
Even if peak values are only measured in the distance, a trip to the Mediterranean is enough for bathing holidaymakers to still find warm water.
A bath in the North Sea or the Baltic Sea should be a rather short pleasure at a maximum of 17 degrees.
Some people are no longer going into the sea: the water in the North and Baltic Sea has a maximum of 18 degrees this week, according to the German Weather Service (DWD).
