The Red Sea in Egypt comes to 28 degrees.
Five fraternity members charged with death of Baruch College freshman
Nearly two years after a student died during a bullying ritual at a student union in Pocono Mountains, Pennsylvania, murder charges are being filed against five people.
Members of New York's Baruch College Pi Delta Psi fraternity brutally attacked Chun "Michael" Deng during an introductory ritual in September 2013 and delayed his transportation to the hospital, which contributed to his death, police said.
Officials said he was blindfolded with a 30-pound backpack full of sand and repeatedly attacked while trying to walk across a frozen field toward a target.
Mr. Deng eventually complained of headaches, then fell unconscious.
Members of the Pi Delta Psi fraternity did not call 911 after Deng fainted and reportedly waited an hour before taking him to a hospital, police said.
However, they had time to change Deng's clothes, Google his symptoms and contact Andy Meng, the Brotherhood's national president, for advice, Police Chief Chris Wagner said at a news conference.
"At this point, the members began to hide paraphernalia and put the welfare of the Brotherhood above that of Michael Deng," Police Chief Wagner said.
He could not be revived and died of his injuries the next morning.
According to an autopsy report, Deng suffered repeated blunt force injuries to his head, torso and thigh.
"Too many families have been destroyed by the fraternity's harassment, with at least one student dying from the harassment every year since 1970," Douglas Fierberg, a lawyer representing Deng's family, said in a statement.
Brotherhoods and their members must be held accountable, and this move by authorities is very important.
A Monroe County grand jury recommended a third-degree murder charge for the first five members.
Thirty-two members of the Brotherhood, including Mr. Meng, are also charged with harassment and forming a criminal organization.
"We don't just want to hold the individuals involved accountable, but if there is an organization that has sanctioned this - officially or unofficially - we will hold them accountable," Wagner said at a news conference on Tuesday.
Baruch College has banned the Brotherhood, and the National Brotherhood has revoked its affiliation with the local chapter.
That's what will happen if the Fed raises rates
A rate hike will come, and the bullish will falter, bond yields will rise, and the economy will slide into recession.
We know that.
What we don't know is how long it will all take and how long it will last.
In particular, history provides little guidance for the economy.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve's aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial assets react.
As a result, US central bank officials have emphasized so strongly that investors should focus not on when it begins to raise interest rates, but rather on the period of time needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants may find that all the excitement about a rate hike may have been exaggerated.
"The Fed's first hike since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as signaling the end of the era of" cheap money, "" Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a note to clients.
By contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to normal levels, but still too low to cause the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
This does not mean, however, that there will be no impact.
Here is a look at how some sectors of the economy might react, based on historical trends:
As the market saw last month, anticipating rate hikes can make things volatile for a while.
Once the increase arrives, the impact is not so dramatic.
"There seems to be a tendency for asset yields to stall 12 to 24 months after the first hike, perhaps reflecting the delay in monetary policy," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of what happens after Fed rate hikes.
More specifically, for the past 35 years, the market has mostly been on an upward trajectory - about 14% - toward a rate hike, fairly flat in the 250 days after (average gain of 2.6%), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return over the past six cycles of 14.4%, according to a recent analysis published by Bob Doll, chief investment strategist at Nuveen Asset Management at Barron's.
Deutsche Bank said the impact on equities tends to occur later in the raising cycle and the yield starts to decline.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but rate hikes often encourage them.
In the current case, the Fed is facing some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
Most remarkably, gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point if the Fed raises interest rates.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 rate hikes since 1950, nominal GDP has been below 4.5% only twice.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect it to last, and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Raising interest rates in such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky, raising the question of "whether this time is different," Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been bracing for a Fed rate hike all year, and all eyes were on this week's Federal Open Market Committee meeting, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could authorize a hike this session, futures trading indicates only a 25 percent chance.
"In our study, all cycles of increases from 1950 to the present have occurred in a super-cycle with increasing momentum in GDP, dwarfing pre-recession highs very quickly after the recovery began," the report said.
By contrast, this is a distinctly slow recovery from what has been the worst recession in the observed period.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and 74 months so far.
Fixed income has also been volatile, as the market anticipates a rate rise and the pattern is quite similar to that in the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on equities when they change their strategic course.
For bonds, yields seem to change direction as soon as the first increase / fall in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the raising cycle, bond yields fall immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab strategists believe that the rise in interest rates will cause yields between longer and shorter bonds to move closer together, flattening the curve.
High-yield bonds often deliver better returns in such a climate, though "we are still cautious about expecting higher returns," Kathy Jones, fixed-income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
What's interesting, Jones says, is that markets have already adjusted to Fed strategy expectations.
"In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adjusted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy," she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit spreads have widened, and volatility has increased - all features of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
By and large, companies that do most of their business in the US will benefit as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinationals with high levels of debt will be worse off, as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market, as well as financing their debt.
"History shows that" quality "stocks tend to react extremely positively three months after an initial rate hike," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for clients.
Firms with strong balance sheets outperformed those with weak balance sheets by an average of 5 percentage points after each of the rate hikes in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high returns on capital and low volatility in their stocks also outperformed their low-quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points), respectively.
Debt is going to be a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of pure equities, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see profits from higher returns, although experts disagree on how quickly that will happen.
BBC Radio 3 is a copy of Classic FM, says MP Andrew Bingham
The Conservative MP criticised the broadcaster for its "dumbing down"
He argues that he is increasingly indistinguishable from commercial rivals.
He also took aim at the BBC Music Awards, saying they only imitated The Brits
Fellow MP Damien Collins attacked the programme The Voice, saying it was not very original.
BBC Radio 3 is "morphing" into Classic FM, a leading MP has claimed, piling fresh pressure on the broadcaster to prove it is doing something private broadcasters do not.
Conservative MP Andrew Bingham also told BBC bosses that the public service broadcaster was "dumb" and increasingly indistinguishable from its commercial rivals.
"Radio 3 seems - I don't like to use the word" dumb "- but it seems to be morphing into Classic FM," he said.
He also took aim at the BBC Music Awards, which kicked off last December.
The BBC Music Awards, which kicked off last year, only seem to be under a different name.
So if you're trying to do something different - these are two spontaneous examples where you're actually just imitating what's already on the market, "Mr Bingham said.
BBC director-general dismissed the allegations, arguing that BBC Radio 3 is way ahead of its commercial rivals when it comes to live music and educating the public.
What I'm learning from Radio 3, I'm not going to learn about classical music anywhere else.
And there is a commitment to live music and making music that is truly second to none.
"And I think Radio 3's commitment to finding new music and commissioning new works is really important," he said.
Earlier this year, BBC Radio 3 controller Alan Davey argued that audiences needed to work harder than they did in the past because Britons are less informed about classical music.
Radio 3 was not the only element of the BBC production to come under fire during the Culture, Media and Sport Select Committee hearing for trampling on its commercial rivals.
Tory MP Damien Collins attacked The Voice - the BBC's musical talent show bought by Dutch producer Talpa Media for an estimated £22 million.
