Four-fold increase in hand sanitizer use by children in the last 4 years
Poison control centers in the U.S. have reported a nearly 400 percent increase in the number of children under the age of 12 swallowing heavily alcoholic hand sanitizers, according to the Georgia Poison Center.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Center, cases of hand sanitizer use in children under 12 who report poison control centers rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"Children are increasingly coming to these products, and unfortunately a percentage of them end up going to the emergency room," Lopez told CNN.
He said some children drink disinfectant intentionally, while some do it to impress their friends or because of a social media backlash.
Videos on YouTube show teenagers drinking disinfectants just for a cheap experience.
Teenagers allegedly mixed disinfectants with alcoholic mouthwash to get a harder drink.
Younger children can be attracted by the attractive scents of disinfectants.
"A child doesn't think this is bad for them," Lopez said.
Many of the more attractive (hand disinfectants) are those that are perfumed.
There are disinfectants with strawberry, grape and orange scents, which are very appealing for children.
Hand sanitizers contain somewhere between 45 and 95 percent alcohol.
Especially in young children, even a few splashes can lead to alcohol poisoning.
"It's highly concentrated alcohol," Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the Poison Emergency Center at the University of Kansas Hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansa City.
So, you wouldn't leave a sip of whiskey standing around, but people leave these hand sanitizers within reach of kids, and when kids get to it, it's a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who had recently taken four squirts of strawberry-scented hand sanitizer at school, was taken to an emergency room for treatment.
Her blood-alcohol level was 179, twice the legal limit for an adult to be drunk, said Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room physician who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah slurred her words and was unable to walk when she arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight at a separate children's hospital for signs of brain trauma because the girl had fallen through the alcohol and hit her head, Ritchey said.
"It was very scary," Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah's mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal for my child.
Lopez has advised parents and teachers to use alcohol-free products or disinfectant wipes and to keep hand sanitizers out of the child's reach.
Beyond alcohol poisoning, some disinfectants have been linked to deaths.
In 2013, two Ontario women died after swallowing hand sanitizers containing a toxic, undeclared ingredient.
Health officials suspect the product contained methanol, a lethal solution, rather than ethyl alcohol, which was listed as an active ingredient.
In January, three New York State fourth-graders planned to poison their "mean" teacher by putting antibacterial products around the classroom, according to a police report.
