The Federal Constitutional Court has ruled in favour of an ex-prisoner of the Tegel penitentiary, who was housed for months in a cell that was too small.
Due to the violation of their human dignity, prisoners are in principle entitled to financial compensation if they are housed in cells that are too small.
This was decided by the Federal Constitutional Court in a decision published on Wednesday.
According to the judges, those affected can hope for money even if they were locked up in the too narrow rooms for only a few days (file no.: 1 BvR 1127 / 14).
Thus, an ex-prisoner was successful with his constitutional complaint in Karlsruhe: Between June and November 2009, he was housed in a solitary cell in the Berlin-Tegel penitentiary with about five square meters of floor space; the toilet was not physically separated.
The man, who has since been released, according to his lawyer, had been moved to a larger cell.
His suit against the state of Berlin for official liability because of the undignified conditions of detention failed.
But the constitutional judges overturned the verdict of the Berlin Court of Appeal and dismissed the case there for re-examination.
They see the human dignity of the man being violated.
Court of Appeal now decides on amount of compensation
Even if, for legal reasons, only a few days "detention from the period in question is decisive for compensation, a claim for compensation is made, it was stated.
Otherwise, "a deterioration of the legal protection of the personality would be to be feared."
The Court of Appeal must now clarify the amount of monetary compensation.
Constitutional judges have often in the past strengthened the rights of prisoners.
As recently as April, for example, they awarded damages to an inmate for being locked naked in a cell.
According to a 2011 decision, the multiple occupancy of a cell without a separate toilet is also unworthy of human beings.
On Wednesday, Karlsruhe also confirmed the Berlin Constitutional Court, which had certified an inhumane accommodation for a prisoner in a parallel case in November 2009.
The plaintiff at that time was accommodated daily for three months between 15 and 21 hours in a cell of the same type as in the Karlsruhe case.
Berlin's prisons have also hit the headlines in recent weeks for a lack of staff.
