Robot cars: Government wants to lead the way for Germany
According to the will of the Federal Government, Germany should be a technological pioneer in the transformation of the car.
On Wednesday, the Federal Cabinet adopted a strategy paper drawn up by Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which, among other things, envisages investments in the expansion of digital infrastructure.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the sidelines of the International Motor Show (IAA) of a "new age of mobility."
Automated and connected driving will increase road safety and reduce congestion, Dobrindt said.
He also intends to discuss the issue with his counterparts from the G7 countries, who will also meet with representatives of industry at the IAA.
Among other things, the strategy paper of the Ministry of Transport emphasises the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a rapid transition to digital radio.
A test track is currently being built on the 9 motorway in Bavaria to test new technology.
To ensure that "no additional liability risks are imposed on the driver," the Federal Government wants to "review the legal framework conditions and, where necessary, adapt them to new developments."
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to raise the speed limit for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometres per hour.
The Federal Government also wants to push for an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
In automated driving, the car increasingly takes the lead, and the driver becomes more and more of a passenger.
The technology is based primarily on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study presented by the Ministry of Economics, highly automated driving on motorways will be technically possible by 2020.
Nonetheless, driverless vehicles on public roads are "not expected until well after 2020," he said.
The authors of the study estimate that the value added in the area of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions in Germany will amount to around 8.4 billion euros in 2025.
"The digital networking of cars can lead to greater safety and efficiency in road traffic," said SPD transport politician Sören Bartol.
However, the question of liability in the event of accidents and the safety of drivers' personal data must be clearly clarified.
However, Germans are still sceptical about self-driving cars - much more so than the French or Americans.
A survey by the Forsa Institute on behalf of the test organisation Dekra, presented on Wednesday at the AA, comes to the conclusion that only eight percent of Germans believe that autonomous cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32 percent do not expect it to happen until 20 years from now, and 31 percent do not believe it at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomous cars by 2025, and 33 percent in the United States.
In any case, drivers in Germany are not yet ready to completely rely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to cede control on all roads during the entire journey.
On the motorway, 15 per cent could imagine this in flowing traffic, and 45 per cent in traffic jams.
Just over one in four would not leave control to the car under any circumstances.
