Gaultier feels too old for an enfant terrible
It is a mixture of a very large fashion show and a wax figurine horror cabinet: designer Jean Paul Gaultier (63) presented an exhibition of his work in Munich on Wednesday.
The highlights: mannequins that look frighteningly human thanks to video projections.
They wear the spectacular creations of the French designer, who became a big star of the fashion scene with Madonna's stage outfits - and by putting men in skirts.
'I can't say I'm the enfant terrible of haute couture anymore because I have white hair. '
"It used to be bleached, now it's real," Gaultier said.
For visitors to the exhibition "From The Sidewalk To The Catwalk," on view from 18 September at the Kunsthalle der Hypo-Kulturstiftung, it is fortunate that the fashion designer has changed his initially negative attitude towards a show about himself.
Actually, he was against it, because "to me, an exhibition sounded a bit like death," he said.
When you die, you go to the museum.
The impressive collection had previously made stops in Montreal, Canada, and Paris.
"It's about so much more than just beautiful clothes," said the Kunsthalle's director, Roger Diederen.
It is about tolerance, acceptance and the vision of an open society.
The exhibits provide an insight into the hard-to-overview work of the man who has written fashion history without ever having completed any training.
The show is not chronologically structured, but it is an excellently choreographed synthesis of the arts, for which a great deal of effort was put into it: for example, a stylist was hired to style the dolls.
According to the curator Thierry-Maxime Loriot, the makers transported 14 tons of material to Munich.
Shortly before the start of the Oktoberfest, there was another special treat: a Lederhosen outfit with a corset.
Heidi meets Madonna.
He has always been interested in strong women ("women are smarter than men") and people who are a bit different, Gaultier said.
Gaultier's old teddy can also be seen in the exhibition.
It represents the designer's first tentative attempts at fashion.
As a child (he was not a good student and bad at football), Gaultier said, he put bras and clothes on his teddy bear.
His parents would not have allowed him to play with a doll.
He later taught himself how to design fashion.
He stole fashion magazines and looked at the designs of other designers, Gaultier said in Munich.
Later I bought them, of course.
He couldn't pay the models for his first fashion show of his own.
They got nothing, but were allowed to keep the clothes.
Jewellery instead of curtains - Plauen lace as a fashion niche
In the old days, the long embroidery machines in and around Plauen were all about making meters.
The embroidered fabrics and lace were made in large quantities for customers, who processed them into blankets and curtains, for example.
That alone does not work today any more, explains Andreas Reinhardt, managing director of the fashion point Plauen.
Instead, fashion is important again.
In the early days of the Plauen lace, fashion played a larger role, was then supplanted by the home textile industry - and is now being rediscovered as a niche.
Reinhardt gives a few examples: lace in jewelry, accessories such as bags and regional costumes.
In general, so-called vintage fashion, which is based on past stylistic epochs, represents an increasing potential for commissions.
Anyone who does not serve niches in the textile industry in Germany is no longer on the market.
With us, they already account for half of all orders.
Fashion lace Plauen is a member of the industry association Plauener lace and embroideries together with nine other companies.
Only they are allowed to wear the protected label.
In the last 15 years, around 80 per cent of turnover has gone.
There are almost no more private specialized shops and also the wholesale trade.
Our products hardly reach the customer in this way any more.
Nowadays, mass-produced goods are much cheaper in the Asian region and are sold almost exclusively through chains.
Exports, currently to Russia and the US, are also weakening.
Enough reasons, then, for new paths.
The industry association also tries to score points through environmental awareness, as Cordula Bauer from Stickperle in Falkenstein explains: "Since this year, we have been carrying a seal of quality that shows that we produce in an ecologically and socially compatible way."
Reinhardt adds: "This also applies to the materials used."
Degree designer Ute Schmidt teaches at the Schneeberg branch of the Westsächsische Hochschule Zwickau - at the Faculty of Applied Arts - and specialises in embroidery and lace.
In order to counteract the competition from the Asian region, one has to find high-quality and innovative products.
It takes time and courage.
A field of tension arises between the freshest ideas of the designers and the enterprises, which must think above all economically, "says Schmidt.
Therefore, an existing design is often only slightly varied in order to maintain a customer base.
A few years ago, textile designer Kati Reuter revived the historic snowball lace.
The machine embroiders small balls in some places.
The Plauen goldsmith Bianca Hallebach-Krauße was inspired by this: "Before, I couldn't do anything with traditional Plauen lace."
Now she uses the snowball tip for her jewelry.
She embosses the pattern in silver using an elaborate process.
"Many people in the region identify with the topic of Plauen lace - young and old," says Reuter.
It also delivers to the USA, Australia and Finland - especially to customers whose ancestors lived in Plauen and its surroundings and who would like a souvenir.
I see my jewellery as a modern ambassador for the Plauen lace.
