Xi Urges Wider Opening of Economy to the World
The economy needs to open up more to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told a group tasked with steering the reform on Tuesday.
"China should work to attract foreign investment and know-how and improve business start-up strategies," he said in a speech at the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group for Deepening Comprehensive Reform.
Promoting start-ups and pushing ahead with reforms will bring new impetus and vitality and provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The leadership group has adopted a number of directives, including a negative list to regulate market access, relaxation of border control policies, promotion of state-owned enterprises (SOE) to raise private capital, and overhaul of the population reporting system.
According to the statement, a negative list will be drawn up identifying sectors and companies that are not eligible for investment.
The system is gradually being tested and improved by means of test programs.
The initiative is important because it gives the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensures a rule of law business environment and makes the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also relax controls on the powers conferred on companies and ensure that companies decide how they conduct their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border areas to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
As part of an offer to open up state-controlled sectors, further areas will be opened up to private investment.
"The government will not change its foreign investment policy and will protect the legitimate interests of leveraged companies and provide better services to them," the statement said.
It will also make it easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or green card by optimising requirements and facilitating the application process.
The right of lawyers to carry out their work and to appoint professional judges and prosecutors was also discussed at a meeting.
The meeting was also attended by Premier Li Keqiang and key leaders such as Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement released after the meeting.
EU to double mercury limit in predatory fish
The European Commission wants to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fish, thereby requiring consumers to consume significantly higher doses of the nerve agent.
The consumer organisation Foodwatch, which has received a working paper from the EU, strongly criticised the plans: "Risks and side effects of failed industrial and environmental policies are passed on to pregnant women and young children with full force," explained Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limit values for nerve toxins for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as sharks or swordfish, are to be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic reasons."
Large predatory fish are already so heavily contaminated with mercury, however, that around 50 percent of catches may not be sold on the basis of the still valid limit values.
After doubling the limit values, only 14.5 percent would then be unsellable.
In exchange for this relaxation, according to Foodwatch, the EU wants to tighten the limits for other fish from the current 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
However, Foodwatch described this as a "trick" because smaller peacefish, such as carp, are usually so low polluted that they are already meeting the planned maximum levels.
The reduction in small fish is therefore "a perfidious diversionary manoeuvre that only helps the economy," Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a heavy metal that is highly toxic to humans and accumulates strongly in predatory fish in particular through the food chain.
The Federal Government therefore warns that "even small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in unborn children."
However, with regard to the current maximum values, the Federal Environment Ministry declares on its homepage that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury is released into the environment mainly through coal combustion.
The German coal-fired power plants emit more than six tonnes of mercury a year, two thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany, according to a written statement from the Federal Environment Ministry to Greens member of the Bundestag Annalena Baerbock.
The concentration of mercury in fish in areas such as the Elbe, Rhine and Danube was "permanently and comprehensively exceeded," Der Spiegel had quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, Europe-wide warnings about mercury in fish were already among the most frequently reported health hazards in the EU's RASFF alert system.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest against the EU's plans at: www.mercksilber-aktion.foodwatch.de
